    description: "Date: March 28, 2025 (Friday)Time: 12:00 p.m. - 12:30 p.m. (This presentation will be held virtually via Zoom.)Presenter: Miss Junlin Wang, PhD candidateSupervisors: Professor Y. Su (Primary Supervisor) & Professor J.J. Wang (Co-supervisor)Join Zoom Meetinghttps://hku.zoom.us/meeting/register/G_kk2vfmQKSGKBmJC1yGhgMeeting ID: 958 2152 0662Password: 892939Title: Multi-omics integration of tumor microenvironment heterogeneity in CE and NE regions of high-grade gliomaAbstract:Because the metastasis of the NE region of high-grade glioma cannot be completely removed by surgery, this residual tumor leads to the recurrence of high-grade glioma. We used WES, scRNAseq, and Bulk RNAseq to systematically study the mechanism of tumor regulation and microenvironment regulation in the NE region. In this study, we found that the tumor microenvironment in the NE region showed very strong neural specialization, accompanied by dysregulation of excitatory and inhibitory synapses. This may be due to the effect of SLITRK2 on PTPRD receptors of glial cells such as neurons, resulting in changes in the communication mode of each cell so that the tumor cells can adapt to the environment. Abnormal activation of the NRG-ERBB pathway and SLIT2-ROBO pathway in the NE region is observed in neurons, which makes the microenvironment more suitable for tumor survival and metastasis and results in neurologic imbalance. The FGF signal between tumors is also significantly enhanced, which will promote drug resistance and the malignant development of tumor cells. Tumor cells also secreted a large amount of PTN to act on OPC, which significantly promoted the transformation of OPC into oligodendroglia. As a result, in bulk RNAseq deconvolution of patients, OPC in the NE region was significantly lower than that in the CE region, and the proportion of oligodendroglia in the NE region was significantly increased, which destroyed the balance of the original neural microenvironment. These changes in the neural microenvironment of tumors in the NE region also explain the causes of complications such as brain function injury in patients to a certain extent. In the evolution of myeloid cells, we found that the overall NE region tends to be an immunosuppressive microenvironment, which may be caused by the general lack of the MIF signaling pathway in the NE region. At the same time, we observed the mutation of cell cycle ADRA1B, which led to the down-regulation of the corresponding cell cycle-related pathway in the NE region. These partial results suggest that tumors in the NE region tend to sacrifice a certain degree of growth in exchange for hijacking the nervous system to accelerate metastasis. The blocking of  these signaling pathways may be one of the ideas of postoperative targeted therapy. Date/Time28/03/202512:00-12:30LanguageEnglish",
